and","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1396–":"1396–Deceased","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Deceased","1392–1471":"1392–1471","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1445–Male":"1445–Deceased","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1471":"1471","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","about 1409":"about 1409","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1410":"about 1410","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Poulton, Wiltshire, England":"Poulton, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goddard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Gothard","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","English: occupational name for a keeper of goats, from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>hierde</i>) ‘herdsman, keeper’.","English: variant of <b>Goater</b>, with excrescent <i>-d</i>, either a topographic name for someone who lived by a stream or ditch, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + the agent suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, or an occupational name either from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> ‘goatherd’ or from Middle English <i>goter</i> ‘goatherd’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>got(e)</i> ‘goat’ (Old English <i>gāt</i>)."]},{"name":"Godard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Reynald, Alcide, Armand, Aurel, Celine, Cyprien, Dominique, Emile, Etienne, Euclide, Gilles.","French: from the personal name <i>Godard</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Goddard  ).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Goddard  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Goertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Christoph, Erwin, Guenter, Juergen, Kurt, Otto.","German (also <b>Görtz</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Goert</i>, a short form of <i>Godhard</i> (see   Goddard  ),   Gottfried   or   Gerhardt  , common in Rhineland.","Germanized form (also <b>Görtz</b>) of Sorbian <b>Gerc</b>; see   Gertz  ."]},{"name":"Goodart","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Gothard  ."]}]},{"name":"Ciecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":59,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Ciecily Goddard was born in 1396, in Poulton, Wiltshire, England, her father, John Goddard of Poulton, was 27 and her mother, Cecily Mildenhall, was 24. She married Thomas Fisher about 1409, in Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in England."},"et":{"1396–":"1396–Surnud","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1392–1471":"1392–1471","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1471":"1471","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","about 1409":"umbes 1409","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1410":"umbes 1410","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Poulton, Wiltshire, England":"Poulton, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1396–":"1396–Kuollut","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1392–1471":"1392–1471","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1471":"1471","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","about 1409":"noin 1409","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1410":"noin 1410","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Poulton, Wiltshire,